---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { getMeta, getAllEntities, latestOf, prettyDate } from '../lib/data.mjs';
const meta = getMeta();
const entities = getAllEntities().sort((a, b) => a.name.localeCompare(b.name));
const title = `Methodology & sources — ${meta.title}`;
const description = `The formulas and official sources behind each rate series in ${meta.title}, plus how the post-judgment rate is derived from the Federal Reserve H.15 1-year Treasury yield.`;
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>Methodology &amp; sources</h1>
  <p class="lead">Each series below shows its authority, how the value is obtained, and its confidence.</p>

  <h2>The rate series</h2>
  <div class="scroll-x">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Series</th><th>Latest</th><th>Effective</th><th>Basis</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {entities.map((e) => {
          const l = latestOf(e);
          return (
            <tr>
              <td><a href={`/rates/${e.slug}/`}>{e.name}</a></td>
              <td class="num">{l?.value_text}</td>
              <td>{prettyDate(l?.effective_date)}</td>
              <td class="source-note">{l?.confidence === 'high' ? 'Published' : 'Derived'}</td>
            </tr>
          );
        })}
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h2>IRS §6621 rates</h2>
  <p>The IRS sets its interest rates each quarter as the <em>federal short-term rate</em> plus a fixed
    spread that depends on the category: +3 points for underpayments and non-corporate overpayments,
    +2 for corporate overpayments, +5 for large corporate underpayments, and +0.5 for the GATT portion
    of large corporate overpayments. We read the published quarterly figures directly from the IRS and
    record each with its effective quarter — these are <strong>published</strong> values.</p>

  <h2>The federal post-judgment rate (28 U.S.C. §1961)</h2>
  <p>Federal law defines this rate as the <em>weekly average 1-year Treasury constant maturity yield</em>
    for the calendar week preceding the date of judgment. The U.S. Courts publish that <em>rule</em> but
    not the number. We compute it from the Federal Reserve's official H.15 1-year Treasury series (daily),
    averaged by week, and label it a <strong>derived</strong> value with medium confidence. Always confirm
    the exact applicable week against your district court's own published table before relying on it.</p>

  <h2>UK statutory late-payment interest (Late Payment Act 1998)</h2>
  <p>UK statutory interest on late commercial (B2B) debts is the Bank of England base rate plus 8
    percentage points — but it is <em>fixed for six-month periods</em> using the base rate in force on the
    reference date: 31 December (for debts falling due Jan–Jun) or 30 June (for Jul–Dec). We track the
    Bank of England base rate directly (published) and compute the semi-annual statutory rate from it
    (derived), applying the correct reference date for each period.</p>

  <h2>EU Late Payment Directive reference rate (2011/7/EU)</h2>
  <p>The Directive's reference rate is the ECB main refinancing rate in force on the first calendar day of
    each half-year (1 January / 1 July); a member state's statutory rate is that reference plus at least 8
    percentage points (the floor most states use; some add more). We track the ECB main refinancing rate
    directly (published) and compute the semi-annual reference (derived). Apply your member state's margin
    to get the statutory rate.</p>

  <h2>Data sources</h2>
  <ul class="clean">
    {meta.sources.map((s) => (
      <li><strong>{s.publisher}</strong> — {s.name}. <a href={s.home_url} rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank">{s.home_url}</a>. {s.license}</li>
    ))}
  </ul>

  <h2>US state judgment rates</h2>
  <p>State rates come in two kinds, and we treat them differently. <strong>Statute-fixed</strong> rates
    (California 10%, New York 9%/2%, Massachusetts 12%) are written into the law; we verify them against
    the official statute text (the legislature's own site), cite the section, record the carve-outs, and
    re-verify on a schedule — the page shows the verification date. <strong>Market-linked</strong> rates
    (Iowa: 1-yr Treasury + 2%) are computed weekly from the same official H.15 series as the federal
    rate, with the statutory formula cited.</p>

  <h2>Coverage &amp; roadmap</h2>
  <p>The dataset covers U.S. federal statutory, judgment, and tax interest rates; U.S. state judgment
    rates (18 states: CA, NY, TX, FL, GA, PA, OH, IL, NC, MI, NJ, VA, WA, AZ, CO, TN, MA, IA); U.K. statutory late-commercial-payment interest and the Bank of
    England base rate; and the EU Late Payment Directive reference rate and ECB main refinancing rate.
    Planned expansion: more U.S. states (TX, FL, WA next), and per-EU-country late-payment margins.</p>

  <div class="disclaimer">Reference data, not legal, tax, or financial advice.</div>
</BaseLayout>
